name "chap:Background"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the field of forensic science the idea of a hierarchy of propositions is well established 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cook1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There is a common understanding within the forensic community that the offence-level propositions are for the fact-finder (aka the judicial system/jury) to address 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson2019,Evett2002,Schaapveld2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The area of remit for the forensic practitioner is the assessment of lower level propositions (activity,
 source,
 sub-source,
 and sub-sub-source).
 In many jurisdictions,
 this assessment is provided to the fact-finder in the form of a Bayesian likelihood ratio describing a numerical amount of support for one of two mutually exclusive propositions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bayesian statistics is based on the premise of belief in some information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bolstad2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Collected data is analysed in the presence of a person's pre-existing knowledge and prior experiences.
 In Bayesian statistics,
 this prior knowledge or belief in a situation is depicted using of a prior probability distribution which is used to determine the plausibility of the prior belief when faced with new data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bolstad2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The use of Bayesian statistics in forensic science intuitively aligns with the way that judicial systems decide on criminal culpability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Shengelia2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In recent years,
 as forensic analytical methods become accepted by the judicial system,
 focus has turned from source level propositions to questions of how or when the analysed evidence was deposited 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There is still some reticence within the global forensic community on who the appropriate assessor of activity-level propositions should be with some practitioners feeling that it is not within the remit of a forensic practitioner 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Prinzetal2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However more than half (56%) of global forensic practitioners that were surveyed in 2024 held the opinion is that it is the role of the forensic expert witness to speak to possible activities that result in the detection of trace DNA evidence (defined as evidence with no obvious attributable body fluid source) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Prinzetal2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Often lawyers pose questions in an effort to gain clarity from the statistical expert witness testimony or to find a method to find alternative explanations for the results.
 Questions are generally put forward in the form of what the possibility/probability of a given scenario which could give rise to trace evidence transfer having occurred might be.
 A majority of respondents to a survey of forensic practitioners in the United States in 2022 had been asked to give testimony on DNA transfer (80%) or activity-level propositions (almost 60%) in the preceding three years 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yangetal2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A following worldwide survey from the same group found testimony on DNA transfer (almost 68% of respondents),
 activity-level propositions (51% of respondents) and consideration of DNA given possible activities (59% of respondents) has been widespread over the last three years 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Prinzetal2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with addressing such questions in the courtroom is that opinion that is given is not backed by a robust statistical support framework and has not been peer-reviewed to ensure consistency and accuracy.
 Members of a judiciary system are likely to misunderstand the weight of evidence that should be given to source-level or lower findings without training in the consideration of what the pertinent question of interest is for a case 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ENFSI2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For example,
 if a suspect is the owner of a vehicle used in a crime,
 whether their DNA is a match to that recovered from the steering wheel may be irrelevant to the question of who committed the crime.
 
\end_layout

