\begin_layout Standard
Each vertex's state is drawn from a finite set of possible states with some probability of observance.
 Vertex probabilities represent the complete set of possibilities for the vertex and are mutually exclusive.
 The probabilities of the states are stored in a table,
 either as probabilities conditional on the state of the parent vertices or,
 if there are no parents,
 as marginal or unconditional probabilities for the vertex.
 In this paper,
 for simplicity,
 these tables will be referred to as conditional probability tables (CPTs) in all cases.
 CPTs can be filled from experiments by the practitioner that mimic case circumstances;
 published probabilities similar to the case;
 a range of reasonable values;
 or based on the practitioners prior experience or knowledge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schaapveld2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The CPTs of each vertex are used to calculate the joint probability of a proposition by the equation in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:jointProb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 below.
 This equation is based on an assumption known as the Markov Property that individual vertices are independent of all preceding vertices except its direct ancestors.
 The Markov property enables a simplification to the joint probability calculation for a scenario as there can be a reduction made to the number of factors that are involved.
 This is important as more complex BNs are developed as required computational power is a limiting factor constraining the usability of networks.
 As computation power availability grows,
 more complex BNs can be developed.
 The Markov property creates a characteristic that the state of a vertex is conditional only on the state of its parents and not the state of any other vertex in the network,
 known as conditional independence.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:simpleBN"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 vertices A and D are conditionally independent.
 Additionally,
 the possible state that a child node may take may be dependant on the state of it's immediate parents,
 a characteristic known as being conditionally dependant.
\end_layout

