\begin_layout Section
Bayesian Networks in Forensics 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:BNsInFornesics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
BNs can be used to support the assessment of opposing propositions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Evett2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Information obtained from evidence is used to inform a framework of circumstances and utilises the hierarchy of propositions to guide the description of relationships between vertices 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Evett2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Bayesian Networks have been used in forensic science applications since the late 1980s 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BiedermanTaroni2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Initially,
 as a means of investigating sub-source propositions such as the inference of profiles from mixed DNA samples,
 they began to be used to represent the relationships at higher levels as scientists found them to be a useful method of explaining the interaction of the pertinent evidence.
 Forensic applications face complications due to the highly dynamic nature of crime,
 where no two cases will be exactly the same.
 Concerns around the use of BNs in forensics include the subjectivity of the CPTs in networks assembled by different practitioners.
 Choosing appropriate prior distributions and likelihood values are forced to rely on a framework of assumptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Biedermann2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In some cases,
 the question of interest will be treated as having been likely to occur with equal probability or disregarding prior knowledge,
 such as in the process of determining the likelihood of two competing propositions where each can be considered equally plausible prior to examining evidence.
 Others may have a vast array of pre-existing knowledge,
 such as allele frequencies in the local population in determining the likelihood of a DNA profile.
 However,
 there is a number of cases,
 such as during the assessment of activity-level propositions,
 when the question has little or no supporting data to inform it.
 In the absence of an non-coerced confession from a suspect,
 the ground-truth of all instantiations of a network can not be known (ie whether a suspect's DNA was on the knife handle from the incident rather than coincidentally).
 Due to the highly dynamic nature of crime,
 previous casework samples cannot be reliably used to inform prior probabilities for any node.
 When independently analysing a case,
 the single data point that is presented will have very little impact if there is a lot of pre-existing knowledge,
 and will be highly impactful if there is very little existing knowledge.
 The values that describe the prior distribution are then highly subjective to the analysts existing knowledge and awareness of published literature.
 Published data is sparse or even non-existent for many situations,
 and for situations with suitable data,
 it is reliant on the case manager to be aware of them.
 This has caused many in the field to feel that no testimony on evidentiary support for activity-level propositions should be offered.
 However,
 the experience of scientists in their field often provides an understanding of typical presentations of evidence that would provide more context to evidentiary support than is provided when just reporting on source or sub-source propositions.
 R v Atkins and Anor.
 (2009) and R v Reed and Anor (2009) are just two examples from one jurisdiction where the presiding judges have stated that opinion based on an expert's years of experience and with sufficiently reliable underlying science should be shared with a jury if it provides a mechanism for the evaluation of the evidence within the scope of the case circumstances
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "thomas_regina_2009,hughes_regina_2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.The discrepancy of knowledge between different experts makes it extremely difficult to gain consensus across the forensic community.
 This may lead to disagreements between experts in the courtroom,
 complicating the the decision to be made by the fact-finder.
 Kokshoorn et al (2018) have attempted to address the issue for DNA cases by creating a publicly available spreadsheet database called 'DNA-TrAC'.
 It is a collection of summary information about published transfer,
 persistence,
 prevalence and recovery (TPPR) studies for DNA to enable practitioners from around the world to be aware of existing literature on the topic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DNA-TRAC2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However,
 contributing to DNA-TrAC is voluntary and so the collection is limited and updates occur sporadically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assessment of the network to determine the effect of the values used is important to ensure the evaluation is robust and limitations are understood 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schaapveld2019,ChenPollino2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Although there have been many advancements in causal model algorithms in the field of artificial intelligence in recent years,
 there is a lag in the transparency or explainability of outputs derived from these complex models that makes them less attractive to a forensic or legal context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As networks become more complex there has been a move to save sub-networks of common processes to allow for reuse in other networks.
 These are termed object-oriented Bayesian Networks (OOBNs),
 which has opened the door to the creation of highly complex and large networks by embedding the sub-networks within the larger network.
\end_layout

